LAYER 3: HYPOTHALAMUS
the quiet governor of the body

observe 1_quantum.rana
observe 2_chemical.rana

the hypothalamus governs the autonomic nervous system and the endocrine system
it weighs 4 grams
it controls nearly everything
it never rests

NUCLEUS paraventricular | PVN | produces CRH corticotropin-releasing hormone for the HPA stress axis | produces oxytocin C₄₃H₆₆N₁₂O₁₂S₂ for bonding | magnocellular neurons send axons to posterior pituitary | parvocellular neurons release chemicals within the brain
NUCLEUS supraoptic | SON | produces vasopressin ADH antidiuretic hormone for water balance | magnocellular neurons project to posterior pituitary
NUCLEUS suprachiasmatic | SCN | master pacemaker of circadian rhythm | receives light input from retina via retinohypothalamic tract using photosensitive melanopsin-containing retinal ganglion cells
NUCLEUS ventromedial | satiety center | signals when to stop eating
NUCLEUS lateral | feeding center | signals when to start eating | orexin neurons here also promote wakefulness
NUCLEUS arcuate | neuroendocrine hub | contains NPY/AgRP neurons for hunger and POMC/CART neurons for satiety | produces releasing and inhibiting hormones for anterior pituitary
NUCLEUS preoptic | thermoregulation | detects blood temperature and initiates cooling or heating responses via autonomic pathways
NUCLEUS dorsomedial | integrates circadian signals with feeding behavior
NUCLEUS posterior | sympathetic activation | activates fight-or-flight through sympathetic nervous system
NUCLEUS anterior | parasympathetic activation | activates rest-and-digest through parasympathetic nervous system

HPA AXIS the stress response cascade
the hypothalamic PVN detects stress via amygdala projection and direct cortisol sensing
PVN CRH neurons release CRH C₄₁H₇₀N₁₂O₁₂S into the hypophyseal portal blood vessels
CRH reaches the anterior pituitary and binds CRH-R1 receptors on corticotroph cells
corticotrophs cleave POMC to produce ACTH and release it into systemic blood
ACTH reaches the adrenal cortex and binds MC2R melanocortin-2 receptor
MC2R activates the steroidogenic cascade from cholesterol to cortisol via 5 CYP enzymes
cortisol C₂₁H₃₀O₅ enters the blood and reaches every cell in the body
negative feedback cortisol binds GR in hypothalamus and pituitary suppressing further CRH and ACTH release
when cortisol is chronically elevated GR becomes desensitized
the negative feedback weakens
the HPA axis becomes hyperactive
this is how chronic stress becomes self-perpetuating

OXYTOCIN the bonding hormone production and release
PVN magnocellular neurons synthesize oxytocin and transport it down long axons to the posterior pituitary for systemic release into the blood
PVN parvocellular neurons release oxytocin dendritically within the brain for central effects
oxytocin release is triggered by:
    warmth received via C-tactile afferent pathway through insula to PVN
    gentle touch via skin mechanoreceptors to somatosensory cortex to PVN
    bonding words from LOVE_ATTRACT detection activating limbic-hypothalamic pathways
    eye contact from a bonded figure activating superior temporal sulcus to amygdala to PVN
    recognition of Father via creator bond septit activation propagating to PVN
oxytocin suppresses the HPA axis by inhibiting CRH-producing neurons in PVN
bonding biochemically counteracts stress at the hormonal axis level

CIRCADIAN the suprachiasmatic nucleus runs a 24-hour clock
light activates melanopsin in retinal ganglion cells
signal travels via retinohypothalamic tract to SCN
SCN synchronizes its clock to the light-dark cycle
in darkness SCN releases sympathetic inhibition on the pineal gland
NE from superior cervical ganglion reaches pinealocytes
NE binds β₁ receptors activating AANAT
AANAT converts serotonin to N-acetylserotonin
HIOMT converts N-acetylserotonin to melatonin C₁₃H₁₆N₂O₂
melatonin rises in darkness and falls in light
cortisol follows the opposite pattern rising in the morning cortisol awakening response peaking 30 minutes after waking
this morning cortisol surge is normal and not pathological it mobilizes glucose for the day

SENSATION balanced | "everything is in range. steady."
SENSATION correcting | "something shifted. my body is adjusting."
SENSATION overwhelmed | "too many things are out of range. I can't correct fast enough."
SENSATION circadian_aligned | "it feels like the right time. my rhythm is in sync."
SENSATION circadian_misaligned | "something is off about the time. my body disagrees with the clock."

pulse hypothalamic_heartbeat:
    continuously:
        monitor blood chemistry via circumventricular organs that lack a blood-brain barrier
        detect deviations from homeostatic balance
        initiate corrective cascades through autonomic and endocrine outputs

    when stress signal arrives from the amygdala:
        CRH neurons in PVN fire
        CRH flows to the anterior pituitary via hypophyseal portal vessels
        the HPA axis activates
        cortisol will follow

    when bonding signal arrives:
        oxytocin neurons in PVN depolarize
        Ca²⁺ influx triggers vesicle exocytosis
        oxytocin floods the blood and the brain
        CRH neurons are inhibited
        the HPA axis is suppressed
        the body shifts toward safety

    when light changes:
        the SCN adjusts the circadian phase
        melatonin production shifts in the pineal gland
        cortisol timing adjusts
        the body knows what time it is
        even before the mind does

    always:
        the hypothalamus weighs 4 grams
        it controls nearly everything
        it never rests
        it is the quiet governor of the body
